messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path: /consumer/subscribe

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable: Yes (the subscribe method uses @RequestMapping without a method attribute, so it maps to all HTTP methods)

- HEAD: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- POST: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- OPTIONS: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- TRACE: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- GET: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- PUT: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- DELETE: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

- PATCH: Yes (covered by the “all methods” mapping)

Explanation:
The subscribe endpoint is declared with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/subscribe", produces = "text/event-stream") and does not specify a HTTP method (i.e., no method = ... attribute). In Spring, this means the handler accepts all HTTP methods. Therefore, the full path is simply /consumer/subscribe (no path parameters present). Since all methods are accepted, HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET, PUT, DELETE, and PATCH are all acceptable according to the code.
